@setinstone This is a really interesting discussion, and great writing. Would you say that creativity is incomplete without mastery of the skill it takes form in?

@daveconnis 
This is an interesting question, because it starts to explore how to apply creativity. In terms of functioning in an intuitive"flow state" like I was referring to in the article I think mastery is necessary. Otherwise, your creativity is always bumping up against the limits of your skills. But I also think some of our most creative moments happen when we are just figuring things out, before mastery. If we don't know what we are doing; we just make it up as we go along and these can be incredibly creative moments. But these are less intuitive and more cognitive problem solving moments. I think there is a difference in operation when creativity is purely expressive and when it is creating solutions. I would not say one process is more creative than the other, but the experiences of creativity are very different. I hope this makes sense.

How'd you do the glitches?

I'm doing a few things- I've got a bunch of layers of the same melody, I threw a layer (sometimes a few layers) into a loop pedal which was followed by a fuzz, a couple distortion pedals, octaver, moog resonant filter.

Then those were running into a small tube amp that I stereo miced. 

As I recorded the amp I played my pedals like a weird piano, changing the tone of the fuzz, increasing distorton, sweeping the delay time, changing which octaves were coming out, and opening and closing the envelope on the moog.

And a few other knobs probably.

It's like any other instrument- I start to learn what a small slider change will sound like and I try to use them as instruments.

fields.title: Middle Grade/Scifi Audio Book - (A funny story about aliens and Christmas)
fields.description:
Three Quotes:
1. "In a small village called Guck, on a planet called GuckGuck, lived a small alien named Bix. Bix was small, about as small as an alien that’s precisely three and a half feet high. Bix was also purple and furry. If you can imagine a furry teardrop that also happened to kind of look like a purple mushroom (easy, right?), you can most definitely picture Bix."
2. "Tab held out her hand like a Freeze Ray, her favorite weapon in the Man-In-Suit series. “You’re mine lizardy alien! Pzew, pzew! I am the purveyor of yuletide justice!” 
3. "Bix didn’t seem like a human-eating alien. Even though he could eat cookies in one gulp, human-eating aliens never wore Hawaiian shirts and glasses with a nose and mustache."

Summary:
Bix and Tab: Agents of Yuletide Justice is a middle grade sci-fi comedy complete at 22,000 words. It is akin to a coffee date between Men In Black and The Mysterious Benedict Society.

On Guck-Guck, a planet three light-years from Earth, a little purple alien named Bix decides to visit Earth to research Christmas on the eve of his planet's own wretched holiday, Punch-In-The-Face-Mas. When his spaceship crash-lands in the skating rink of Chicago's Millennium Park on Christmas Eve, he meets a eleven year-old girl named Tab. Tab’s obsession with a series of sci-fi books she believes are real inspires her to ask her parents if Bix can stay at their house for Christmas. However, in the middle of the festive night, Tab and Bix are kidnapped by a secret agency called the Intergalactic Department of Safety and enlisted as junior agents. They are given their first mission: Keep GuckGuck from being destroyed by a group of aliens offended by Punch-In-The-Face-Mas. With help from Tab's deep knowledge of Christmas and science fiction, Bix fights to keep his family and friends from an impending planet-destroying-death-beam explosion.

fields.title: Earth is Inhabited by Zombies, Que the Human Apocalypse (Chapter One)
fields.description:
Some Quotes: 
1. "Hello, wonderful human! Let me be the first to say, “Congratulations” for picking up this book. Let me introduce myself…well, on second thought, that might not be a good idea. For now, just call me, Mr. Narrator, because my real name will just be a distraction to you. Regardless, I’m so glad you’ve decided to try to understand your fellow earth sharers, zombies."
2. Early in his existence, Zed designed a clothing line he called “tattered style,” and it spread like a virus. Tattered Style ended up on fashion runways in New York. Some indie fashionistas you probably haven’t heard of would probably say that he’s the “father of the zombie style.” At one point, Zed even had a zombie CEO call him everyday for a month, asking him to design a line of flavored toothpastes, and every day he would politely respond, “I am not a designer of mouth accessories, but of body clothes.”

Summary:
The first chapter of Zed and the Human Apocalypse. A collision of zombie, the humor of Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy, and gratuitous amounts of irony.

fields.description:
A quick how-to on becoming a Muser Creator...or you could read it below.

 Becoming a Beta Creator
1. Register and make yo'self a profile

fields.title: I Can't Breathe: A Song for Eric Garner
fields.description:
His video's been weighing on my mind, so I just needed to write about it. Here are the words: 

I used to give no worries, about things I couldn’t see
I used to have no problems, with anyone but me
But now when I lay my head down, all I can think of are the things
That I chose not to see

I can’t breathe

I used to have small heartaches, that I could ignore
I’ve never felt my skin in such a way before
There’s men dying in daylight, boys in the park
Does black mean lives gone dark

I can’t breathe

Our systems are a maze of pain, and silent privilege
but life is life just the same, no matter the skin
I’m lost in death, but found in hope and this what I’ll give
the anthem of a call for change. A song for those who didn’t live


If you want more of my music go to www.daveconnis.com
Also, consider supporting me at www.patereon.com/daveconnis

LTLE is a zine that makes space for incoherent and unfeasibly specific ideas/words via the format of letters to the editor.

I’m the letter editor. The letters can be about anything - current news, old news, personal rants & loves, responses to past letters, or they can be about no discernible topic. The point is that their incoherence, worthlessness or extreme specificity will present no obstacle to their publication.

This is issue 1. It contains 10 letters from 9 letter-writers. I wasn't sure what category this should be in. It's sort of writing, but also sort of not-writing.

fields.title: Transatlanticism
fields.description:
Transatlanticism is my very first novel. It is inspired by memories cross bred with artistic license, a love for music and a desire for optimism.

When British student Tom meets Laura one fateful New Year's Eve the two form a connection that will change their lives forever. Staying up all night they bond over dreams, regrets, aspirations and a mutual love for all things music. In the span of just a few hours the two fall helplessly in love. However the one problem standing between them is the fact that Laura is set to return home to Texas in just a few days. Inevitably the challenges of time and distance push the pair apart from one another and for the next ten years they are guided down separate paths. That is until their individual journeys cross once more. But after so much time apart and with so much between the points of then and now can things ever really be the same? Can the spark that ignited so much in the pair of them ever be recaptured?

I don't know where I'm going, but I know it's not here.
If you know where I'm going, then you know it's not here.
All these paper people, in all these paper towns.
I'm not one for flimsy, so I won't stick around.

Ooh, I'll see you on the other side, man
Ooh, I'll leave a place for you to hide, friend
Ooh, one day you'll all see
Oh, the way you saw me was fake, man

I won't be coming back, I'm going to Agloe

Give me just a second to remind you I'm not a mirror maker.

fields.title: Margaret Park Fine Art
fields.description:
My painting has evolved into an increasingly deeper spiritual journey.  As I move ever closer to a clearer connection with the central core of me, my work grows in uniqueness and becomes a clearer definition of not only me but what art is to me. 

The image forms from deep inside, slipping out through fingers and emerging on to the substrate. When it is done, its identity is obvious. Each creative event continues with its storyline until exhausted -- at least for now. Then a new life event, or lack of, evolves into a new storyline. Fact or fiction at the start is always fact in the end. The subconscious does not make it up, it just tells you about it.

fields.title: Handmade Les Paul Replica - "Afterglow" Burst
fields.description:
This is a hand built Les Paul replica carved in Chattanooga, TN. Like the originals, I used Tennessee Sugar Maple for the top and African Mahogany for the body / neck. Instead of the traditional spray-on nitrocellulose finish, I chose to go with a hand rubbed stain and French polished shellac. I like to feel the wood, not a thick plastic-like finish.

Minimalistic with superior tone, this "Afterglow" Burst is one beautiful instrument!


Unfortunately, I can't link you directly to the photo album. The title of it is called "Fly Free Les Paul."

fields.title: strange stranger
fields.description:
I have a lot of dissociative/hallucinatory experiences where people’s faces (my own face included) seem to morph and alter into something other than what they are. Actually, in my experience, nothing is “what it is” because it spends too much time being something other. The “is” can’t hold onto any usable meaning.

My new hobby is drawing these portraits, copied from models in magazines, but altered in the direction of non-human (which is any direction you care to choose, I suspect). I have made self-portraits in this vein too, but I’m reluctant to draw anyone I know without gaining their explicit consent beforehand. Sometimes depiction can be a disturbing experience.

fields.description:
Ultimum Minutis EP is an album that ranges from heavy rock guitar riffs to mellow piano ballads. It's a journey of the performer's musical evolution and experimentation in the course of two years. The band experiments with different elements and effects influenced by post rock bands, as can be heard in Attitudes Pasionnelles, a song recorded with an electric violin only and Terpsícore.

Overall, the album takes the listener on a journey of rock music in its raw form to a more complex and experimental sound.

fields.title: Morning of Indiana
fields.description: On our way to Chicago early one Saturday morning, my wife and I saw this Indiana sunrise. Up until this past year, the entirety of my life had been spent in the Appalachian foothills where the horizon is much less defined, and even lost in the rolling of the hills. Indiana has offered me a new perspective with every morning as the sun peeks over a linear horizon. I find comfort in its steadiness.
